**Section 1: User Story**

**1.1** **Epic Story**

As a Notice Processing Officer who needs to follow up against notices in the OCMS, I want the OCMS to allow me to permanently suspend the processing of notices, so that the notices will not continue to be processed.

**1.2 User Stories **

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

**1.3 Key Functions &amp; Features**

| Functions | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Permanent Suspension (PS) Function | Permanent Suspension (PS) is a function within OCMS that stops the processing of Offence Notices at their current stage. Pre-defined PS codes are used to specify the reason of suspension. |
| Manual Apply PS via the OCMS Staff Portal | The OCMS Staff Portal provides a user interface for authorised OICs to manually apply PS to notices. |
| Auto PS during Notice processing in OCMS Backend | Auto PS can be triggered automatically in the OCMS Backend by pre-defined scenarios ). Suspensions are applied automatically based on conditions and scenarios defined in the OCMS system design. |
| PS initiated by PLUS System | OCMS provides an API to allow the PLUS to initiate PS requests for the following use cases: Appeal Processing Officers can permanently suspend a Notice under specific circumstances, for example, the Appellant is a valid season ticket holder. |
| Generation of Permanent Suspension Report | OCMS Staff Portal’s Report module allows users to export a report to review Notices which were suspended over a time period |

**Section 2 – Permanent Suspension (PS) Function**

**2.1 Use case
**

- Permanent Suspension (PS) may be applied to Notices as they progress through the standard Notice Processing Workflow.

- A PS is applied when a Notice no longer requires further processing within the Notice Processing Workflow. Examples of scenarios include notices which has been fully paid and notices waived by the Appeal Processing Officer during appeal processing.

- When PS is applied, a suspension code will be used to indicate the reason of suspension. 
- Notices can be permanently suspended through the following modes:Manual suspension by EPU OICs via the OCMS Staff Portal
- Automatic suspension by the OCMS backend when pre-defined scenarios occur during batch processing, for example Notices issued to military vehicles are suspended with PS-MID if they are still outstanding at the end of the second reminder stage to prevent the Notices from escalating to the Court stage
- Manual suspension by PLU Officers via the PLUS Staff Portal 

- When a PS is applied to an Offence Notice: The Notice remains at the last processing stage it is currently at.
- The Notice will not advance to the next stage when the Next Processing Date is reached.
**2.2 High-Level Processing Flow**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

| No. | Process | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-conditions | Manual apply PS from Staff Portal: EPU user manually apply PS from OCMS Staff Portal PLU user manually apply PS from the PLUS system Staff Portal. Auto apply PS by the OCMS Backend: OCMS backend auto trigger the PS when pre-defined conditions are met. |
| 1 | OCMS and PLUS Staff Portals check if the PS request is allowed | The OCMS Staff Portal and PLUS Staff Portal will perform an initial check to determine whether PS is allowed. For example, PS-APP can be applied to a fully-paid Notice with an existing PS-FP suspension. If the suspension is not allowed, the Portal will display an error prompt in the UI to inform the User that the suspension is not allowed. The process ends. If the suspension is allowed, the Portal will proceed to Step 2. |
| 2 | OCMS and PLUS Staff Portals proceed to submit PS request via API | The OCMS Staff Portal will call the OCMS backend API to process the PS request. The PLUS Staff Portal will call the PLUS backend API to request for suspension. The PLUS backend will then call the OCMS backend API to process the PS request. |
| 3 | OCMS backend checks if PS is allowed | OCMS backend proceeds to validate the request to determine if the requested PS can be applied. The validation of the request is based on the rules of suspension which have been pre-defined in the backend. If the suspension is not allowed, the OCMS backend responds with an error message to the requesting system and the process ends. If the suspension is allowed, the OCMS backend proceeds to apply the suspension and update the Notice information. |
| 4 | End | The process ends after OCMS has updated the suspension information and responds to the requestor. |

- **Applying Permanent Suspension **
- Notices can be manually suspended by EPU OICs via the OCMS Staff Portal. Refer to Section 3.

- Notices can be automatically suspended by the OCMS backend when pre-defined conditions are met during Notice processing. Refer to Section 4.

- Notices can be manually suspended by PLU OICs (also known as PLMS) via the PLUS Staff Portal. Refer to Section 5. 

- When applying a PS, a Suspension Code must be provided. The Suspension Code indicates the reason for suspending the Notice. 

- Unlike Temporary Suspensions, when PS is applied, the Suspension will not have a Revival Date.

2.5 PS Suspension Codes **

- The list below outlines all the PS Suspension Codes that can be processed by OCMS. 

- The list of PS Suspension Codes can be managed using the Suspension Reason module in the OCMS Staff Portal. *Refer to Section 5 of the OCMS 39 – Parameters Management Functional Document.
*

| Code | Reason of Suspension | Scenario |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ANS | Advisory Notice | The notice will be suspended for the following reasons: Notice data received from external sources (e.g., Certis EHT, PLUS, EEPS) indicates the notice is an AN (Advisory Notice). During checks performed before creating the notice, it meets the criteria to be designated as an advisory notice. |
| APP | Appeal Accepted | Notice suspended as an Appeal has been approved by Appeal Processing Officers. |
| CAN | Cancelled Advisory Notice | Notice suspended as Appeal Processing Officers decide to cancel the suspended Advisory Notice. |
| CFA | Cancelled By Field Admin Unit | Suspension code is used for incorrect issuance by the Parking Warden (e.g., wrong offence details). |
| CFP | Court Fine Paid | Court Fine has been collected by the State Court. This code will be implemented post-MVP after the Court Notices processing workflow has been developed. |
| DBB | Double Booking | Duplicate notices have been issued for the same offence. The second notice will be suspended as a double booking notice. |
| DIP | Diplomatic Vehicle | Diplomatic vehicle Notice is outstanding at the end of the RD2/DN2 stage and is suspended to prevent it from escalating to the RR3/DR3/Court stage. |
| FCT | Foreigner Cannot Be Traced | Offender is a foreigner and cannot be located for follow-up actions. |
| FOR | Foreign Vehicle | Notice has been issued to a foreign vehicle. |
| FP | Fully Paid | Notice has been fully paid |
| FTC | Foreigner Left the Country | Offender is a foreign national who has left the country and cannot be contacted for follow-up actions. |
| IST | Instalment Plan Granted | An instalment plan has been issued to Offender for payment of the Court Fine. This code will be implemented post-MVP after the Court Notices processing workflow has been developed. |
| MID | MINDEF Vehicle | Notice has been issued to a Singapore military vehicle. |
| OTH | Others | Suspension code is used for all other scenarios which have no specific suspension codes. |
| PRA | Payment with Reduced Amount | Partial payment occurred because the Notice escalated to the next processing stage while the payment was being made. The reduced amount has been accepted. |
| RIP | Motorist Deceased On or After Offence Date | Offender died on or after the Offence Date |
| RP2 | Motorist Deceased Before Offence Date | Offender died before the Offence Date |
| SCT | Singaporean Cannot Be Traced | No information can be found for the local offender |
| SLC | Singaporean Left the Country | The local offender has left the country. |
| SSV | Singapore Security Vehicle | OICs have verified that the vehicle is a security vehicle. |
| VCT | Vehicle Cannot Be Traced | Vehicle information not found during LTA ownership checks and has been verified by OICs |
| VST | Valid Season Ticket | Vehicle has a valid season ticket for the parking place. |
| WWC | Withdrawn with Composition Amount | Court Notice at CSD stage and beyond has been fully paid. This code will be implemented post-MVP after the Court Notices processing workflow has been developed. |
| WWF | Withdrawn with Fine | Court fine has been collected by URA. This code will be implemented post-MVP after the Court Notices processing workflow has been developed. |
| WWP | Withdrawn without Payment | Court Notice at CSD stage and beyond has been permanently suspended due to non-payment related reasons, for example defendant passed away. This code will be implemented post-MVP after the Court Notices processing workflow has been developed. |

**2.5 Permanent Suspension Rules **

**2.5.1 Global Rules for Permanent Suspension**

| Condition | Rule | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Displaying PS in the Staff Portal | Display the most recent active suspension | Where there are multiple suspensions (PS or TS) applied to a Notice, the Staff Portal’s Notice Overview tab displays the most recently applied active suspension on screen. |
| Apply new EPR Reason of Suspension PS Code to a Notice with an existing PS Suspension | Allowed for authorised users | Only authorised OCMS OICs and PLU PLMs are allowed to apply a new PS Suspension Code to a Notice with an existing PS. When a new PS is triggered via the OCMS or PLUS Staff Portal, OCMS will revive the existing PS with the revival code '‘PSR’( Permanent Suspension Revival ) and apply the new PS automatically. This rule applies to all Notices with any existing and active PS Suspension. |
| Apply new CRS Reason of Suspension PS Code to a Notice with an existing PS Suspension | Allowed for OCMS Backend during payment processing | Only OCMS backend is allowed to apply PS-FP and PS-PRA during payment processing The following existing and active PS codes allow new PS-FP and PS-PRA suspensions to be applied without revival: DIP FOR MID RIP RP2 PS-FP and PS-PRA cannot be applied to notices with other existing and active PS code that are not listed in (2). |
| Apply TS to a Notice with an existing PS | Depends on existing PS Code | TS cannot be applied to a Notice that has an existing PS. The following PS Codes are exceptions and allow TS to be applied on top of the existing PS: DIP MID FOR RIP RP2 The TS-UNC Suspension Code cannot be applied to any notice with an existing PS, including the ones listed in point 2. |
| Apply PS to a paid or partially paid Notice | Depends on new PS Code | Paid notices are suspended with: PS-FP – Fully paid notices are PS-PRA – Paid at reduced amount Only PS-APP, PS-CFA and PS-VST can be applied on top of paid notices. The suspension will trigger OCMS backend to trigger a refund. For MVP, OCMS will only store the date the refund was identified. |
| Apply PS to a Notice up to CFC and CPC stages | Depends on new PS Code | The following PS Codes can be applied to Court Notices up to CFC and CPC stages: APP CFA DBB FCT FOR FP FTC OTH PRA RIP RP2 SCT SLC SSV VCT VST For MVP, OCMS will not process Court Notices. |
| Notices are payable via the eService or AXS | Allowed for selected case | Outstanding Notices with the following PS codes are payable: DIP MID FOR RIP RP2 |
| Notice is furnishable via the eService | Not Allowed | Notices with a PS are not furnishable. |
| New Hirer/Driver can be added via the OCMS Staff Portal | Not Allowed | Outstanding Notices with the following PS codes need to be revived first before new hirer/driver are added via the OCMS Staff Portal: DIP MID RIP RP2 |
| New Hirer/Driver can be added via the PLUS Staff Portal | Not Allowed | Outstanding Notices with the following PS codes need to be revived first before new hirer/driver are added via the PLUS Staff Portal: DIP MID RIP RP2 |
| Notice can be linked to an Appeal | Allowed | All notices, regardless of its Last Processing Stage and suspension/payment status, can be linked to an Appeal. |

**2.5.2 Suspension Code Rules **

- The OCMS backend maintains a set of rules governing the application of PS to Notices and whether Notice processing operations such as Update Hirer/Driver are allowed.

- The rules will include: Which codes can be applied by PLUS System Users 
- Which codes can be applied by OCMS System Users 
- Which codes can only be applied by the OCMS backend system 
- Which Processing Stages allow or disallow PS
- Whether Update Driver/Hirer can be applied to notices with existing PS
- Whether Reduction can be applied to Notices with existing PS

- PS Suspension Code Rules

MGG proposes to store the rules listed in the database, so that the backend system uses the data to validate the PS requests and permissions. 

**2.6 Validating Permanent Suspension Requests**

**2.6.1 Key Validation Principles 
**

- All requests to apply PS to Notices will be validated. 

- When a PS request is initiated from a Staff Portal (OCMS or PLUS):The Staff Portal will perform the first round of validation based on the valid offence notice data the portal received from the OCMS backend.

- If the Notice(s) are determined to be eligible for PS, the Portal will trigger the PS request to the OCMS backend, which will also perform another round of validation against all rules for PS. 

- When a PS request is initiated from the Backend, for example auto apply PS-RIP, the OCMS backend will also validate the request to determine if the suspension can be applied. 

**2.6.2 Validating PS Requests in the Staff Portal (OCMS and PLUS)**

- The Staff Portal performs first-level validation to provide immediate feedback and prevent invalid suspension requests from being sent to the backend system.

- The Staff Portal submits suspension requests to the backend only if the first-level validation confirms the Notice’s eligibility.

- This approach improves user experience as it:Provides instant feedback so users know immediately if a Notice is ineligible
- Guides users to deselect invalid Notices before submission
- Checks known eligibility rules (e.g., processing stage, PS status) upfront
- Prevent obviously invalid requests from reaching the backend
- The following checks will be performed on the UI side, based on valid offence notice data received from the backend:

| What to Validate in UI | Description |
| --- | --- |
| User Permission | The Portal checks if the user is authorised to perform PS |
| Notice’s Last Processing Stage | The Portal checks the Last Processing Stage to confirm whether the Notice is at a stage that permits PS |
| Payment Status | The Portal checks the following fields to verify if the Notice has been paid: Suspension Type CRS Reason for Suspension |

**2.6.3 Validating PS Requests in the OCMS Backend**

- The OCMS Backend is the main processor for PS requests. 

- The PS function in the OCMS Backend can be triggered by the following sources:

| Source | Scenario |
| --- | --- |
| OCMS Backend | Auto trigger PS when the Notice Processing workflow encounter exceptions, for example: Notice qualifies as an Advisory Notice Offender died before/on or after the Offence Date Offender receives duplicate notice for the same offence instance |
| OCMS Staff Portal | OICs manual PS one or more Notices |
| PLUS Staff Portal | Appeal Processing Officers (PLMs) manual PS one or more Notices for specific reasons, for example: An appeal is accepted, and the Notice is waived It has been verified that the Appellant has a valid season ticket and therefore the Parking Offence Notice is invalid |

- When the OCMS Backend receives the request to perform PS, it will check and enforce:

| Rules | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Authentication of Source and Permission | Source has a valid token for the API call Source is allowed to trigger suspension for the given Suspension Code |
| Global Rules | Last Processing Stage is at a PS-permissible stage Checks to determine if the Notice has been paid |
| Suspension Code Specific Rules | Requestor has permission to suspend with the specific Suspension Code |

- The Backend validation serves as the final safeguard that ensures that the system’s suspension rules are enforced consistently and securely.

**Section 3: OCMS Staff Portal Manual PS**

**3.1 Use case**

- The manual PS function in the OCMS Staff Portal allows authorised OICs to permanently suspend Notices.

- Authorised users can search for the notices using the Staff Portal’s Search Notice function by:Entering search parameters to retrieve one or more Notices
- Uploading a spreadsheet containing a list of notice numbers to retrieve the Notices.

- From the search results, Users can apply PS using one of two ways: Select one or more Notices in the Search Result interface and trigger the PS operation from the drop-down list to initiate a batch PS
- Click on a Notice to view the details and apply the PS from the View Notice Details interface 

- When the PS is initiated from the Staff Portal, the Staff Portal validates the suspension eligibility of each Notice before redirecting Users to the Suspension Detail Page to: Select the PS Suspension Code 
- Input Suspension Remarks, if any
- After the Suspension Details are submitted, OCMS sends the suspension details to the OCMS backend for processing. 
- If PS is successful, Users will be presented with a success message on screen; an error message will be displayed is the suspension is not successful. 
**3.2 Process Flow

**![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| No. | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | OIC wishes to apply PS to one or more Notices. |
| 2 | Search for Notice(s) | OIC uses the Search function to retrieve the Notice(s). |
| 3 | Select Notice(s) | OIC selects the Notice(s) to apply PS to. |
| 4 | Check whether OIC has permission to apply PS | Staff Portal detects whether user has permission to apply PS If OIC does not have permission for OIC, the “Apply PS” function will not be displayed in the Apply Operation drop-down list. And the user journey ends. If OIC has permission to apply PS, the “Apply PS” function will be displayed in the Apply Operation drop-down list. The user will proceed to Step 5. |
| 5 | Check Notice’s Last Processing Stage (LPS) | Staff Portal proceeds to check the Notice’s Last Processing Stage to determine whether PS can be applied to the Notice(s): If PS is not allowed at this LPS, the Staff Portal display the list of Notice Numbers with the message "Unable to PS the following Notice(s) at this Last Processing Stage”. If PS is allowed at this LPS, the Staff Portal proceeds to Step 6. Refer to Section 2.6.2 of this document. |
| 6 | Redirect to Suspension Detail Page | The Staff Portal redirects the user to the Suspension Detail Page which displays these items: Suspension Type drop-down list = Auto populated with PS Select the Suspension Code from the drop-down list Suspension Remarks (alphanumeric, max 200 chars) |
| 7 | Input Suspension Details &amp; Submit | The User enters the Suspension details and clicks the “Apply” button. |
| 8 | Check whether PS can be applied | The Staff Portal begins to detect: Whether the Notice(s) has any active PS suspensions Whether any of the Notice(s) has been paid Notices which are eligible for PS are sent to the OCMS Backend for PS processing. Notices which are not eligible for PS will not be sent to the backend for PS processing. Refer to Section 2.6.2 of this document. |
| 9 | Send eligible Notices to the OCMS Backend for PS processing | The Staff Portal calls the OCMS Backend API to send eligible Notices to the backend for suspension. |
| 10 | OCMS Backend Checks if PS is Allowed | The OCMS backend validates whether the PS request is allowed under the system rules. If one or more Notice(s) is not eligible, the OCMS Staff Portal backend responds to the Staff Portal with an error message. If the Notice(s) is eligible, the OCMS backend responds to the Staff Portal with a success message. |
| 11 | Staff Portal displays PS Success or Fail Message | After receiving the result from the OCMS backend, the Staff Portal displays the suspension results in the table (list) of Notices. |
| 12 | End | The process concludes. |

| PS | RIP | OIC has investigated and verified that the Offender died on or after the Offence Date Note: Manual PS vis the Staff Portal is used if the OCMS backend fails to auto PS the Notice |
| PS | RP2 | OIC has investigated and verified that the Offender died before the Offence Date Note: Manual PS vis the Staff Portal is used if the OCMS backend fails to auto PS the Notice |
| PS | SCT | OIC has investigated and verified that no information can be found for the local offender |
| PS | SLC | OIC has investigated and verified that the local offender has left the country and cannot be located |
| PS | SSV | OIC has investigated and verified that the vehicle is a security vehicle |
| PS | VCT | OIC has investigated and verified that vehicle information cannot be obtained |
| PS | VST | OIC has investigated and verified that the vehicle has a valid season ticket. |
| PS | WWC | OIC has verified that the Court Notice is fully paid by the Defendant. Note: For MVP, OCMS will not process Court Notices. Manual PS vis the Staff Portal is used if the OCMS backend fails to auto PS the Notice |
| PS | WWF | OIC has verified that the Court Fine has been collected by URA. Note: For MVP, OCMS will not process Court Notices. Manual PS vis the Staff Portal is used if the OCMS backend fails to auto PS the Notice |
| PS | WWP | OIC has verified that the Notice needs to be withdrawn due to specific reasons, for example Defendant passed away. Note: For MVP, OCMS will not process Court Notices. Manual PS vis the Staff Portal is used if the OCMS backend fails to auto PS the Notice |

**Section 4: Auto Permanent Suspensions in OCMS**

**4.1 Use case**

- The OCMS system will automatically trigger Permanent Suspensions to Notices when pre-defined scenarios occur.

- The scenarios are pre-defined in the Notice Processing Workflow at various Processing Stages. 

- When the conditions of the scenarios are met OCMS will automatically Suspend the Notices with pre-defined Suspension Codes and alert OICs about the exceptions. 

**4.2 Scenarios that Auto-Trigger PS**

| Scenario | Suspension Code | Auto Triggered by |
| --- | --- | --- |
| The notice will be suspended for the following reasons: Certis or REPCCS indicates that the notice is an AN. OCMS performs AN qualification checks and determine that the Notice qualifies as an AN. | ANS | OCMS Backend |
| Duplicate notices are detected for the same offence and OCMS automatically suspends the second notice as a double booking notice. | DBB | OCMS Backend |
| Diplomatic vehicle Notice has reached the end of the RD2/DN2 stage. | DIP | OCMS Backend |
| Vehicle that committed the Offence is a foreign vehicle. | FOR | OCMS Backend |
| MINDEF vehicle Notice has reached the end of the RD2/DN2 stage. | MID | OCMS Backend |
| Partial payment occurred due to the Notice escalation and the Notice’s amount payable has been adjusted. | PRA | OCMS Backend |
| OCMS receives the date of death from MHA or DataHive and verifies that the Offender died on or after the Offence Date | RIP | OCMS Backend |
| OCMS receives the date of death from MHA or DataHive and verifies that the Offender died before the Offence Date | RP2 | OCMS Backend |
| OCMS receives payment for the Notice and verified that the notice is fully paid | FP | OCMS Backend |

**Section 5: Permanent Suspension initiated by PLUS**

**5.1 Use case**

- PLUS can apply PS via an API provided by OCMS.
- The PLUS system and PLUS Users will initiate PS under the following circumstances:Appeal Processing Officers (PLMs) suspend a notice when the Appeal is accepted.
- Appeal Processing Officers (PLMs) suspend a notice due to specific reasons, for example the Notice was wrongly issued by the Parking Warden, or the Appellant has a valid season parking ticket.
- When a suspension is initiated through the PLUS Staff Portal or backend, the PLUS system shall provide the suspension details, which will be logged in OCMS in the Suspended Notices database table.

- Upon receiving the request, OCMS validates the submitted suspension data before proceeding with the PS.

- PLUS can apply PS to multiple Notices simultaneously.

**5.2 Process Flow
**![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

**![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)**

| No. | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | OIC wishes to apply PS to one or more Notices. |
| 2 | Search for Notice(s) | OIC uses the Search function to retrieve the Notice(s). |
| 3 | Select Notice(s) | OIC selects the Notice(s) to apply PS to. |
| 4 | Check whether OIC has permission to apply PS | Staff Portal detects whether user has permission to apply PS If OIC does not have permission for OIC, the “Apply PS” function will not be displayed in the Apply Operation drop-down list. And the user journey ends. If OIC has permission to apply PS, the “Apply PS” function will be displayed in the Apply Operation drop-down list. The user will proceed to Step 5. |
| 5 | Check Notice’s Last Processing Stage (LPS) | Staff Portal proceeds to check the Notice’s Last Processing Stage to determine whether PS can be applied to the Notice(s): If PS is not allowed at this LPS, the Staff Portal display the list of Notice Numbers with the message "Unable to PS the following Notice(s) at this Last Processing Stage”. If PS is allowed at this LPS, the Staff Portal proceeds to Step 6. Refer to Section 2.6.2 of this document. |
| 6 | Redirect to Suspension Detail Page | The Staff Portal redirects the user to the Suspension Detail Page which displays these items: Suspension Type drop-down list = Auto populated with PS Select the Suspension Code from the drop-down list Suspension Remarks (alphanumeric, max 200 chars) |
| 7 | Input Suspension Details &amp; Submit | The User enters the Suspension details and clicks the “Apply” button. |
| 8 | Check whether PS can be applied | The Staff Portal begins to detect: Whether the Notice(s) has any active PS suspensions Whether any of the Notice(s) has been paid Notices which are eligible for PS are sent to the OCMS Backend for PS processing. Notices which are not eligible for PS will not be sent to the backend for PS processing. Refer to Section 2.6.2 of this document. |
| 9 | Send eligible Notices to the OCMS Backend for PS processing | The Staff Portal calls the OCMS Backend API to send eligible Notices to the backend for suspension. |
| 10 | OCMS Backend Checks if PS is Allowed | The OCMS backend validates whether the PS request is allowed under the system rules. If one or more Notice(s) is not eligible, the OCMS Staff Portal backend responds to the Staff Portal with an error message. If the Notice(s) is eligible, the OCMS backend responds to the Staff Portal with a success message. |
| 11 | Staff Portal displays PS Success or Fail Message | After receiving the result from the OCMS backend, the Staff Portal displays the suspension results in the table (list) of Notices. |
| 12 | End | The process concludes. |

**5.3 Suspension Codes used by PLUS

5.3.1 Suspension Code**

| Suspension Code | Suspension Code | Reason of Suspension |
| --- | --- | --- |
| PS | APP | PLM has reviewed the Appeal and decided to accept the Appeal and waive the Notice |
| PS | CAN | PLM has investigated the Offence Notice case and verified that the AN should be cancelled. |
| PS | CFA | PLM has investigated the Offence Notice case and verified that the Notice should be cancelled due to wrong issuance by the Parking Warden. For example, Parking Warden entered the wrong Notice details. |
| PS | OTH | PLM suspends the Notice for other scenarios which have no specific suspension codes. |
| PS | VST | PLM has investigated and verified that vehicle has a valid season ticket. |

Criteria 1 ( Date Range only ) PS Suspension Date From* = 2025-09-01 PS Suspension Date To* = 2025-12-02 Criteria 2 PSing Officer Name= ‘John Lee ’ PS Suspension Date From* = 2025-09-01 PS Suspension Date To* = 2025-12-02 Criteria 3 Authorising Officer Name= ‘Jame‘ PS Suspension Date From* = 2025-09-01 PS Suspension Date To* = 2025-12-02 In summary, the base query logic is to fetch PS Notices that meet these conditions: Date Range = NA; OR PSing Officer Name AND Date Range OR Authorising Officer Name = PS AND Date range The base Search Criteria must be used with the search parameters that users input. **Retrieval Parameters for PS Report Functionality &amp; Behavior**

| Functionality &amp; Behavior | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Multi-selection of values | Users can select multiple officer names from the drop-down list, with an option to Select All officers. |

| 1 Year Suspension Period Query Limit | The maximum period for querying suspension dates is one year. If the selected duration exceeds this limit, the system will display the prompt: "The duration between the Start Date and End Date must not exceed a year." |
